3_0	0.0	SAN FRANCISCO _ The U.S.
3_1	0.2	Food and Drug Administration on Tuesday approved a one-a-day pill for attention-deficit disorder that is easier to take and possibly more effective than current three-a-day versions of the commonly prescribed drug Ritalin.
3_2	0.0	The FDA decision is a commercial boost for Mountain View, Calif.'s Alza Corp.
3_3	0.3333333333333333	, which can now enter the $700 million-a-year market for drugs that treat attention-deficit and hyperactivity disorder.
3_4	0.0	ADHD makes it difficult for children to concentrate in class and in many instances makes them hyperactive and unruly.
3_5	0.0	``This is the time of year when parents are making the decision to use or not use ADHD medications,'' said Alza chief executive Dr.
3_6	0.0	Ernest Mario.
3_7	0.0	Mario said the company will immediately start promoting its one-a-day capsule to pediatricians.
3_8	0.0	He said Alza could ship the first pills out of its Vacaville factory ``in a matter of days''.
3_9	0.08333333333333333	The Alza pill is based on the drug methylphenidate, the generic version of Ritalin, which has been used since the 1950s to control ADHD.
3_10	0.05	For the 3 to 5 percent of schoolchildren, mainly boys, who are believed to have ADHD, pediatricians routinely prescribe Ritalin or generic alternatives two or three times a day, generally around mealtimes.
3_11	0.0	Although Novartis, the Swiss drug firm that invented Ritalin, brought out a sustained-release version in 1984, that single-dose pill has not been widely used by physicians.
3_12	0.0	Dr. Ami Goodman, a pediatrician with Kaiser Permanente in San Francisco, said doctors typically prescribe the multiple-dose versions because they think they work better.
3_13	0.0	Goodman said doctors have been hoping for an effective one-a-day version because fewer children will forget to take the drug.
3_14	0.14285714285714285	He said a one-a-day pill would remove the stigma that attaches to kids who must slip off to the school nurse's office for a noon booster.
3_15	0.0	``It's a matter of trying to keep ADHD a more private affair,'' said Goodman, who had no opinion about whether the new Alza formula would be any more effective than Novartis' little-used sustained-release pill.
3_16	0.0	But Dr.
3_17	0.0	Glen Elliot, a psychiatrist at the University of California at San Francisco and an Alza consultant, said the clinical studies leading up to the FDA's approval suggest that Alza has found the time-release technology that works.
3_18	0.0	Alza's secret is the pill itself, which is about the size of a Tic Tac candy.
3_19	0.05555555555555555	The pill's outer coating is actually a dose of the drug, which dissolves quickly and begins circulating through the child's bloodstream when the pill is taken before or after breakfast.
3_20	0.0	But it is what is inside the pill that counts.
3_21	0.0	The outer shell dissolves to reveal a tiny plastic pump filled with a 12-hour dose.
3_22	0.0	The pump works by osmosis.
3_23	0.0	It absorbs water from the body.
3_24	0.0	The water liquifies tiny amounts of drug and pushes the liquified drug out a microscopic hole in the pump at a rate calculated to exhaust the medicine just as the child is finishing homework.
3_25	0.0	The availability of an easy-to-use pill is sure to fuel the debate about whether ADHD is overdiagnosed _ and whether Ritalin or its generic alternatives are overprescribed.
3_26	0.0	Stephen Hinshaw, a psychiatrist at the University of California at Berkeley and an ADHD specialist, was part of a recent National Institutes of Health study that endorsed the effectiveness of Ritalin for controlling ADHD.
3_27	0.0	But, said Hinshaw, who is also an Alza consultant, the problem is that ADHD can be misdiagnosed in two ways: labeling boys with the condition simply because they are rambunctious, while missing girls who may have a form of ADHD that shortens their attention span without making them unruly in class.
3_28	0.0	``The problem is that you can't evaluate ADHD in 10 minutes, but in some places that's all the time you get with your physician,'' Hinshaw said.
