4_0	0.0	CHICAGO (AP) --The nation's pediatricians are being asked to take an active role in diagnosing attention deficit/hyperactivity disorder amid concern that merely rambunctious children are being given unnecessary medication.
4_1	0.29411764705882354	The American Academy of Pediatrics on Monday issued its first guidelines for ADHD, hoping to eliminate incorrect diagnoses and make sure untreated children get the help they need.
4_2	0.0	The guidelines are for children 6 through 12.
4_3	0.0	Most ADHD research has involved that age group, and the academy also said it recognizes that some symptoms can be chalked up to normal rambunctiousness and contrariness in preschoolers.
4_4	0.13333333333333333	However, recent research shows dramatic increases in the use of drugs like Ritalin to treat children with ADHD, suggesting the disorder is either becoming more common or is being overdiagnosed.
4_5	0.0	The academy, the nation's largest group of pediatricians, said it is unclear whether the disorder is being overdiagnosed, because doctors' definitions and treatment of it varies widely.
4_6	0.16666666666666666	The academy said it believes the new guidelines will standardize the diagnosis and make it easier to identify which children really need help.
4_7	0.75	Guidelines for treating ADHD are still being developed.
4_8	0.0	''We'd like to help us all (diagnose) more accurately,'' said Dr.
4_9	0.0	James Perrin, an author of the guidelines and an associate professor of pediatrics at Harvard Medical School.
4_10	0.07692307692307693	Between 4 percent and 12 percent of school-age children --or an average of about 2.5 million, most of them boys -- are believed to have ADHD.
4_11	0.2222222222222222	Symptoms include short attention span, impulsive behavior and difficulty focusing and sitting still.
4_12	0.16666666666666666	Ritalin is often prescribed to increase a child's alertness.
4_13	0.0	But many experts have pointed out that its long-term effects on children are unknown.
4_14	0.07692307692307693	For a diagnosis of ADHD under the new guidelines, a child must exhibit symptoms in at least two settings, such as at home and at school.
4_15	0.09090909090909091	The symptoms must harm the child's academic or social functioning for at least six months.
4_16	0.0	This is the first time the academy has drawn up guidelines for a behavioral ailment.
4_17	0.0	The academy began developing them three years ago, said Dr.
4_18	0.0	Martin Stein, co-author and a pediatrics professor at the University of California at San Diego.
4_19	0.058823529411764705	The guidelines also suggest that pediatricians and family doctors take a leading role in addressing the disorder, with information about the child's behavior from parents and teachers.
4_20	0.2	Doctors also should use criteria from the American Psychiatric Association's diagnostic manual of mental disorders.
4_21	0.1	Involving pediatricians in the diagnosis of ADHD is ''really exciting because they're seeing these kids more than child psychiatrists,'' said Dr.
4_22	0.0	Karen Pierce, a child psychiatrist in Chicago who helped develop the standards.
4_23	0.0	''It will add a new dimension and actually be able to help a lot more kids''.
