11_1	0.125	(AP) --Doctors may be overdiagnosing some groups of children with attention deficit-hyperactivity disorder and overprescribing drugs to treat the condition, according to a new study published Wednesday.
11_2	0.04	Researchers examined about 30,000 grade-school children in two districts in southeastern Virginia and found that pupils took drugs for ADHD in school at two to three times the expected rate, according to the study in the American Journal of Public Health.
11_3	0.375	ADHD is characterized by impulsive behavior and difficulty in paying attention and keeping still.
11_4	0.15789473684210525	About 90 percent of patients take Ritalin, a mild central nervous system stimulant believed to calm hyperactivity by helping the brain disregard distracting stimuli.
11_5	0.0	ADHD has been estimated to affect 3 percent to 5 percent of school-age children nationwide, with less than 3 percent actually receiving medication, said Gretchen LeFever, a pediatric psychologist and lead author of the study.
11_6	0.05555555555555555	By comparison, her research found that 8 percent to 10 percent of children in second through fifth grades routinely took ADHD medication in school during the 1995-96 school year.
11_7	0.0	``It's hard to believe this many children have the specific brain-related problem called ADHD,'' said Ms.
11_8	0.0	LeFever, assistant professor of pediatrics and psychiatry at the Center for Pediatric Research.
11_9	0.0	The center is a joint program of Eastern Virginia Medical School and Children's Hospital of The King's Daughters.
11_10	0.0	Ms. LeFever said there probably are regions across the country with similar trends, indicating more research is needed.
11_11	0.0	``That's a very high rate of ADHD, by anyone's estimate,'' said psychologist Nadine M.
11_12	0.0	Lambert of the University of California at Berkeley, a longtime ADHD researcher who was not involved in the current study.
11_13	0.0	In the study, researchers reviewed records of pupils enrolled in the second through fifth grades in Portsmouth and Virginia Beach.
11_14	0.0	They chose those two cities because they were the most diverse in southeastern Virginia, Ms.
11_15	0.0	LeFever said.
11_16	0.0	Portsmouth is a small, urban, poor, mostly black district while Virginia Beach is a larger, wealthy and mostly white.
11_17	0.2	Researchers also found that ADHD medication was used by three times as many boys as girls and twice as many whites as blacks.
11_18	0.0	Use of the medication increased as children aged.
11_19	0.0	By the fifth grade, 19 percent to 20 percent of white boys received ADHD drugs.
11_20	0.0	Dr. Louis H.
11_21	0.0	McCormick, a faculty member in the family medicine department at Louisiana State University medical school, said the study confirms what he has long suspected in his own 20-year practice, that kids are being overdiagnosed with ADHD.
11_22	0.07692307692307693	The problem is that other conditions, such as anxiety or depression, can mimic the symptoms of ADHD, said McCormick, a family doctor in Franklin, La.
11_23	0.0	, who has given seminars on ADHD.
11_24	0.3333333333333333	He also is a member of the American Academy of Family Physicians.
11_25	0.16666666666666666	``We don't have a blood test to evaluate ADHD.
11_26	0.0	ADHD is an educated guess,'' McCormick said.
11_27	0.0	``... You need better data from all 50 states to really get a handle on the prevalence.''
12_0	0.5	WASHINGTON _ Using a radioactive ``label,'' scientists have demonstrated abnormally high concentrations of a key brain protein in seven adults who had been diagnosed with attention deficit disorder.
12_1	0.1	The test suggests that parents of children suspected of having the learning and behavioral problem may someday be able to have their children tested before deciding whether to have them take potent and controversial drugs such as Ritalin and other stimulants.
12_2	0.0	But Bertha Madras, one of the Harvard Medical School researchers who performed the initial test, said many more experiments must be performed before such a test is available.
12_3	0.0	``The initial data is robust,'' she said Thursday in a telephone interview, ``but a cascade of experiments have to be done before we can say we have a diagnostic tool''.
12_4	0.6875	Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) is a common psychiatric illness that is believed to affect between 3 and 5 percent of children in the United States.
12_5	0.0	In general, it affects such functions as working memory, self-control and motivation.
12_6	0.30434782608695654	Madras, a professor of biopsychology at the medical school, said the test showed that the seven adults diagnosed with attention deficit disorder had on average a 70 percent elevation in concentrations of a brain protein called the dopamine transporter.
12_7	0.058823529411764705	By linking a radioactive iodine molecule to a substance that locks onto the dopamine transporter, the researchers were able to use imaging instruments to directly measure the concentrations of transporter.
12_8	0.0	The study is described in a report being published Friday in the British medical journal, the Lancet.
12_9	0.0	The finding appears to confirm theories about the way ADHD affects its victims, but Madras said tests on larger populations of adults and later on children must be performed.
12_10	0.0	The researchers have applied for Food and Drug Administration approval for a second test with a larger group of adults, she said.
12_11	0.0	(Story can end here.
12_12	0.0	Optional add follows).
12_13	0.0	Psychologists and psychiatrists say the condition seems to affect girls and boys differently.
12_14	0.7857142857142857	Most girls with ADHD have a form known as Type A, which is characterized primarily by inattentiveness and distractibility, and less by hyperactivity and impulsive behavior.
12_15	0.42857142857142855	The most common form among boys is known as Type B.
12_16	0.42857142857142855	Rather than flightiness, persons with this form tend to be hyperactive and impulsive.
12_17	0.375	A Type C involves symptoms of both Types A and B.
12_18	0.8333333333333334	And Type D patients have symptoms that can disrupt everyday life, but none that clearly fit the other three forms.
12_19	0.0	Studies have shown that academic performance of 90 percent of the school-age patients improves with stimulant medication, principally the drug methylphenidate, marketed as Ritalin.
12_20	0.0	However, the treatment is controversial, since methylphenidate shares many of the pharmacological effects of cocaine and is addictive to test animals.
12_21	0.0	It also is one of the most commonly diverted and stolen substances in America, and more high school students are reported to abuse it than receive it under prescription.
12_22	0.1	Moreover, the diagnosis of ADHD is based on behavioral studies and can involve often-subjective judgements on the part of therapists.
12_23	0.045454545454545456	A consensus development panel convened last year by the National Institutes of Health recommended continued use of stimulant drugs for ADHD, but also called for more research toward understanding the nature of the disease and developing a more precise diagnostic procedures.
12_24	0.0	Although the chemical reasons for ADHD are not clearly understood, scientists have speculated that the brain's failure to control the activity of dopamine, a neurotransmitter that relays signals between nerve cells, is involved.
12_25	0.0	Specifically, some researchers believe the transporter protein _ the ``truck'' that moves dopamine from one cell to the next _ is key to the condition.
12_26	0.0	Normally, the transporter protein gathers up the dopamine after it has stimulated its target cells and returns it to the cells that released it.
12_27	0.125	Methyphenidate, cocaine and other stimulant drugs are known to inhibit the transporter protein.
12_28	0.0	By taking the ``trucks'' off the highway, the drugs cause dopamine to build up and continue to stimulate its targeted nerve cells, Madras explained.
12_29	0.0	This has the paradoxical effect of calming persons with ADHD.
12_30	0.0	Some researchers think this is because their condition stems from a deficiency of target cells or of the cell receptors that react with dopamine.
