24_1	0.6153846153846154	New research in mice suggests that drugs such as Ritalin quiet hyperactivity by boosting the levels of serotonin, a neurotransmitter, in the brain.
24_2	0.0	A study appears Friday in the journal Science.
24_3	0.5333333333333333	Between 3 and 6 percent of American school-age children suffer from a condition called attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, or ADHD.
24_4	0.0	These children are restless and impulsive and have difficulty concentrating.
24_5	0.25	Drugs such as Ritalin and Dexedrine have a calming effect, but their action has been poorly understood.
24_6	0.058823529411764705	Howard Hughes Medical Institute researchers at Duke University discovered the serotonin action of Ritalin by eliminating the possibility that the drug was acting on other brain chemicals.
24_7	0.0	They used a laboratory mouse strain that had been genetically manipulated to lack a key protein in the processing of dopamine, another neurotransmitter.
24_8	0.0	Such mice have symptoms similar to those of ADHD.
24_9	0.0	When the mice lacking normal dopamine were given Ritalin, they were calmed, proving that the drug was not acting on dopamine.
24_10	0.1	The researchers then blocked the effects of norepinephrine, another brain chemical, but this had no effect on the ADHD symptoms.
24_11	0.0	Finally, the researchers gave the mice Prozac, a drug that inhibits the action of serotonin.
24_12	0.0	The ADHD symptoms declined dramatically in the mice.
24_13	0.26666666666666666	The results, said the researchers, show that Ritalin acts on the serotonin levels in the brain by restoring a proper balance between serotonin and other natural brain chemicals.
